{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between history management and the LLM request builder (`passed to the LLM`), not just a pure slice helper. A unit test of a trim function can miss wiring bugs where the untrimmed list is sent. Real OS/network/subprocess is not required, and correctness does not depend on model output. Rejected higher levels: no behavior text requires real HTTP/subprocess (so not System) or model judgment (so not Agentic/Workflow).","test_description":"Wire chat service + history trimmer + LLM client adapter in-process; use a spy/stub LLM client and submit >10-message history. Assert outbound LLM payload contains exactly the latest 10 messages in correct order, and assert a regression case where an older message would have been included fails.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This is output-quality validation of the model response itself (`addresses the customer's question` vs generic/off-topic). A stubbed model would always pass and hide true failures in relevance. Rejected higher level Workflow: behavior describes a single generation quality check, not multiple agentic decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Run prompts against the real production model with a fixed evaluation set of customer questions and rubric/scorer for topical relevance; fail if relevance falls below threshold or generic/off-topic rate exceeds limit across repeated runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on model judgment of tone (`correctly identifies ... too formal`), so mocking hides real misclassification. The regeneration trigger can be asserted in the same run without requiring a full multi-step quality evaluation of regenerated content. Rejected Workflow: while regeneration is invoked, behavior text does not require validating multiple model decisions' content quality end-to-end, only that tone detection causes the branch.","test_description":"Use real model calls for initial response + tone-check on a curated casual-tier set designed to provoke formal drafts; assert the tone-check flags formal outputs and that regeneration API path is invoked immediately after flagging.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.58,"Workflow":0.28}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is in local module interaction: chat orchestration -> persistence layer -> DB schema/transaction mapping. This is not model-quality dependent, and can be caught with a real local test DB (or in-process DB) without external OS/network behavior requirements. Rejected System: behavior text does not require real external DB service/network faults, only correctness of persisted records and timestamps.","test_description":"Run chat flow with deterministic LLM stubs that force one regeneration; write to test DB and assert all records exist (user message, first draft, regenerated final), linkage/order are correct, and timestamps are stored correctly and monotonically.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration/state-handoff correctness (response selection after a trigger), not model output quality. It can be tested by forcing tone-check result and verifying outward response channel only emits regenerated content. Rejected Agentic: behavior text does not require judging whether model tone decision is correct, only replacement behavior after trigger. Rejected Workflow: no requirement to validate multi-step model quality, only branch handling and visibility rules.","test_description":"Wire controller/service/output adapter with stubbed LLM and tone-check returning `trigger=true`; simulate two drafts and assert the customer-facing response payload/stream contains only the second draft while the first is suppressed, including race/order assertions in the same process.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.56,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.24,"Workflow":0.15}}]}
